  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3842397029" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3842397029" />
    <a title="Kristina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4272284-kristina"><img alt="Kristina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612241104p2/4272284.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3842397029?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kristina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kristina" href="/user/show/4272284-kristina">Kristina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=can-t-finish">can-t-finish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=can-t-finish-2021">can-t-finish-2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=got-rid-of">got-rid-of</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=disappointing">disappointing</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=hated-em">hated-em</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=my-book">my-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=not-worth-my-time">not-worth-my-time</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4272284-kristina?shelf=magical-realism">magical-realism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3842397029" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1258299505752634139">Well, I tried. My low rating of <i>Mama Day</i> by Gloria Naylor is not a reflection of the novel; it’s my personal inability to like anything about the book. I pretty much hate everything: narration style, characters, and the story itself. I wasn’t going to give up, but when I reached the halfway point and still loathed it, I decided to stop wasting my time. <br/><br/>If you read the publisher’s blurb about the book, it sounds pretty good: Mama Day is a sort of nature goddess/magical matriarch of a place called</span>
  <span id="freeText1258299505752634139" style="display:none">Well, I tried. My low rating of <i>Mama Day</i> by Gloria Naylor is not a reflection of the novel; it’s my personal inability to like anything about the book. I pretty much hate everything: narration style, characters, and the story itself. I wasn’t going to give up, but when I reached the halfway point and still loathed it, I decided to stop wasting my time. <br /><br />If you read the publisher’s blurb about the book, it sounds pretty good: Mama Day is a sort of nature goddess/magical matriarch of a place called Willow Springs. Willow Springs is located on an island off the coast of Georgia, but does not belong to any state; it is a community that still believes in herbal medicine and remembers and honors its slave ancestors. People come to Mama Day for help and she uses her nature-inspired powers to help as she can. However, her great-niece, Ophelia, is stubborn and independent and while she loves Mama Day and her grandmother, she is too caught up in the power of the outside world where she lives and works to see the danger she is in and respect the advice of Mama Day. <br /><br />So, the blurb makes the book sound like some kind of battle for the soul of Ophelia, dark powers vs. the goodness of Willow Springs and Mama Day. However, at halfway in, I don’t see that yet. The story is written in second person narration, a style I absolutely hate. Actually, there are three narration styles: an unknown narrator who addresses the reader directly as “you,” omniscient narration that describes the actions and thoughts of Mama Day and her sister, Abigail and a flip back to second person you but it’s revolving chunks of narration in which the speaker is addressing a “you,” but the “you” is actually another person (rather than the reader). I hate all of it of the second person narration. The large “you” sections are actually two separation conversations: Ophelia talking to George and George talking to Ophelia. But it’s not an actual conversation; it’s like when you’re having an argument/discussion with another person but the conversation is one-sided because it’s all in your head. So you read Ophelia’s thoughts about something then the narration flips to George’s thoughts, generally on the same subject. Mostly it’s about their relationship and how they first met and their impressions of each other, etc. It’s so damn <i>tedious</i>. Ophelia is a portrait of the absolute worst tendencies of women to argue with men about the stupidest shit at the stupidest times (during football games) and make the most ridiculous demands requiring proof of love—she is exhausting and annoying and I can’t stand her. George is a little better, but not much. He goes on and on about his engineering job and his love (obsession) for football, particularly the Patriots (ugh) and jesus, I’ve had enough. I got a few giggles from him when (after he and Ophelia got married) he began reading books to figure out how to live with a woman because he never had (and grew up in a boys home/orphanage) and, to keep biases balanced, he read books with male and female authors and decides (based on hormone cycles) women must be sane only about three days out of the year. That was funny. <br /><br />I gave up on this book because while I find Mama Day and her nature powers intriguing, she’s not in the book enough to keep me reading. There’s too much second person “you” narration between George and Ophelia (and you get the sense they are looking back on these events) and the plot is slow and confusing and the thought of struggling through another 150+ pages is too much. Sorry, Gloria Naylor. I thought I had read this before, but I think what happened is I read her other book, <i>The Women of Brewster Place</i>, loved it and bought <i>Mama Day</i>…then (as is my terrible, terrible habit) I put it on the shelf and promptly got distracted by newer and shinier books. I will try to reread <i>The Women of Brewster Place</i> this year to see if my theory is correct. However, I want to be clear that my dislike of this book is purely ME. The book itself is fine and if you are intrigued by it, go for it. Unfortunately, it just wasn’t my cup of herbal tea.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1258299505752634139" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

