  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2775377894" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2775377894" />
    <a title="gwayle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2514493-gwayle"><img alt="gwayle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1263184933p2/2514493.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2775377894?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="gwayle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="gwayle" href="/user/show/2514493-gwayle">gwayle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2514493-gwayle?shelf=black-writer">black-writer</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2514493-gwayle?shelf=e-book">e-book</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2775377894" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11825527860184235802">Mama Day is an amazing novel in the magical realism genre. Ophelia “Cocoa” Day is descended from a mysterious formerly enslaved women who was deeded the island of Willow Springs. Belonging to neither South Carolina nor Georgia, the island and its all-black community are left to their own devices. But Cocoa has left her birthplace for the grit and glamor of NYC, where before she meets George she experiences the challenges of finding work and finding love in the city as a single black woman.<br/><br/>This s</span>
  <span id="freeText11825527860184235802" style="display:none">Mama Day is an amazing novel in the magical realism genre. Ophelia “Cocoa” Day is descended from a mysterious formerly enslaved women who was deeded the island of Willow Springs. Belonging to neither South Carolina nor Georgia, the island and its all-black community are left to their own devices. But Cocoa has left her birthplace for the grit and glamor of NYC, where before she meets George she experiences the challenges of finding work and finding love in the city as a single black woman.<br /><br />This story is told in three voices: George and Cocoa address each other, while Mama Day, a powerful healer and Cocoa’s great aunt, anchors the Willow Springs plot. It works well. Fate and love and hate and history will collide when Cocoa brings George home for a visit and the pair falls prey to malevolent forces.<br /><br />This novel has one of the best realized settings: the characters, history, geography, and culture of Willow Springs are so richly imagined. Bernice, Dr. Buzzard, the other place, Candle Walk—so, so good. George and Cocoa are real and relatable; I loved their story. And Mama Day, what can I say? What a character! The depiction of family and community, with their comforts and their burdens, also the pain and loneliness of their absence, was wonderful.<br /><br />The Tempest is mentioned in the marketing copy for the book, but don’t expect a retelling—it’s more of a resonance. This moving story stands on its own. The plot was maybe a bit much there at the end, and parts were a touch slow, but overall a lovely and memorable read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11825527860184235802" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

